            </figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/12/10/border-politics-debating-immigration-policy/" data-title="Border Politics: Debating Immigration Policy" data-description="In this lesson we offer three different teaching ideas to engage students in the debate over immigration policy in the United States.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w151 right module">
<div class="entry"><a title="See all Lesson Plans" href="/category/lesson-plans/"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_lesson-plan151.png" alt="Lesson Plans - The Learning Network" /></a><a title="See all lesson plans" href="/category/lesson-plans/"><img class="w35 right" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_lesson-plan35.png" alt="Lesson Plans - The Learning Network" /></a></p>
<h6 class="kicker">Current Events</h6>
<p class="summary">Teaching ideas based on New York Times content.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="/category/current-events/">See all in Current Events Â»</a></li>
<li><a title="See all Lesson Plans" href="/category/lesson-plans/">See all lesson plans Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While America wrestles with how to fix its <a href="//www.businessinsider.com/immigration-data-charts-reform-illegal-2013-1?op=1">&#8220;broken&#8221;</a> immigration system, an estimated 11 million undocumented immigrants live, work and raise families in the United States. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This isn&#8217;t a new problem. Go back in history to the <a href="//www.ourdocuments.gov/doc.php?flash=true&#038;doc=47">Chinese Exclusion Act</a> (1882), the <a href="https://history.state.gov/milestones/1921-1936/immigration-act">National Origins Act</a> (1924) and the <a href="//www.pbs.org/kpbs/theborder/history/timeline/23.html">Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965</a> and it&#8217;s easy to see that we&#8217;re a nation that has been wrestling with immigration issues for a very long time. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In this lesson we offer three different teaching ideas. First, we let students research and debate different policy options addressing the issue of undocumented immigrants today. Second, we ask students to research and respond to President Obamaâs recent executive action granting up to five million immigrants a reprieve from deportation. And third, we encourage students to compare immigration policies and attitudes between different countries to gain a more global perspective on the issue. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And for much more on immigration, including lesson plans, multimedia, and links to current and historical Times articles, visit our collection <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/04/27/learning-about-u-s-immigration-with-the-new-york-times/">&#8220;Learning About U.S. Immigration With The New York Times.&#8221;</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-153009"></span></p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Quick Warm Ups</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As a warm up, teachers may want to ask students to brainstorm a quick list of beliefs and stereotypes that people hold about immigrants, including those without legal documentation. Then watch the New York Times video we have embedded above, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/us/100000003247235/americas-11-million.html">&#8220;Americaâs 11 Million.&#8221;</a> List the ways in which words and images from the video either reinforce or challenge those stereotypes. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another option is to watch and discuss this <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/us/100000002517565/think-back-americas-immigration-debate.html">brief video</a> by  Sam Tanenhaus describing how immigration has evolved through American history, from anti-Irish sentiment in the 1800s to President Reaganâs decision to grant amnesty to 3 million undocumented immigrants. Students can then explore this <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2009/03/10/us/20090310-immigration-explorer.html">interactive map</a> showing immigration data from 1880 to 2000.  </p>
<hr/>
<div class="w480"><figure class="promo media video blog-video "
    data-videoid="100000002517565" data-media-action="modal" data-autoplay="" data-embedded="true" aria-label="media" role="group">
        <span class="visually-hidden">Video</span>

