<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Teaching Idea #1: Researching and Debating U.S. Immigration Policy Options</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For our first teaching idea, we ask students: What should we do about the estimated 11 million undocumented immigrants living in the United States?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Students can research and debate four policy options commonly proposed: mass deportations, pathways to citizenship, a reprieve from deportations with no chance for citizenship and refugee status for recently arrived undocumented minors from Central America. Teachers may want to assign students to one of the four research groups in preparation for a debate, or they may want students to evaluate all four options and choose the policy they think is best.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Mass Deportations:</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In his first five years in office, President Obama deported more than two million unauthorized immigrants. Most were forced to leave the United States after being stopped for minor offenses, such as traffic violations, or for being apprehended near the border.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Do deportations work? Do they stop undocumented immigrants from trying to enter the United States? Would it be feasible to find and deport over 11 million undocumented immigrants? And what would be the consequences for families, communities and the American economy?</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/17/nyregion/families-can-crumble-under-deportation-threat.html">Families Can Crumble Under Deportation Threat</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/us/deportations-dont-lower-crime-rates-study-says.html">Deportations Have âNo Observable Effectâ on Crime Rate, Study Concludes</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/06/us/seeking-to-stop-migrants-from-risking-trip-us-speeds-the-path-to-deportation-for-families.html">As U.S. Speeds the Path to Deportation, Distress Fills New Family Detention Centers</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.thenation.com/article/179099/why-has-president-obama-deported-more-immigrants-any-president-us-history">The Nation | Why Has President Obama Deported More Immigrants Than Any President in U.S. History?</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/07/us/more-deportations-follow-minor-crimes-data-shows.html">More Deportations Follow Minor Crimes, Records Show</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.motherjones.com/politics/2014/04/obama-administration-record-deportations">The Obama Administration&#8217;s 2 Million Deportations, Explained</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/12/23/us/fears-multiply-amid-a-surge-in-deportation.html">Amid Steady Deportation, Fear and Worry Multiply Among Immigrants</a></li>
<li><a href="//lasvegas.cbslocal.com/2013/03/28/study-deportation-doesnt-deter-border-crossings/">CBS Las Vegas | Study: Deportation Doesn&#8217;t Deter Border Crossings</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/02/22/us/politics/growth-in-deportations.html">Growth in Deportations</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/02/17/magazine/do-illegal-immigrants-actually-hurt-the-us-economy.html">Do Illegal Immigrants Actually Hurt the U.S. Economy?</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2011/10/19/us/latinos-said-to-bear-weight-of-deportation-program.html">Latinos Said to Bear Weight of a Deportation Program</a></li>
</ul>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/09/learning/deportationsgraphLN/deportationsgraphLN-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/09/learning/deportationsgraphLN/deportationsgraphLN-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/09/learning/deportationsgraphLN/deportationsgraphLN-blog480.jpg" id="100000003279341" width="480" height="291" alt="&lt;strong&gt;Growth in Deportations 1892-2012:&lt;/strong&gt;Â By the end of 2013, the Obama administration had deported more than two million undocumented immigrants, more than any other U.S. president in history. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/02/22/us/politics/growth-in-deportations.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="291"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"><strong>Growth in Deportations 1892-2012:</strong>Â By the end of 2013, the Obama administration had deported more than two million undocumented immigrants, more than any other U.S. president in history. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/02/22/us/politics/growth-in-deportations.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Path to Citizenship:</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Instead of forcibly removing undocumented immigrants from the United States, should we offer them a clear path to citizenship? Some argue this would be unfair to immigrants who have legally applied for citizenship and are waiting their turn? Others argue that unskilled workers with no family living in the United States have <a href="//www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5404217">almost no chance</a> of obtaining a green card, according to <a href="//reason.org/files/a87d1550853898a9b306ef458f116079.pdf">current law</a> (PDF).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What do you think? Should Congress and the president make it easier for immigrants to become citizens?</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2014/07/17/americans-are-abandoning-their-support-for-a-path-to-citizenship-for-undocumented-immigrants/">Washington Post | Americans Are Abandoning Their Support for a Path to Citizenship for Undocumented Immigrants</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2014/06/24/is-state-citizenship-the-answer-to-immigration-reform">Room for Debate: Is State Citizenship the Answer to Immigration Reform?</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2014/02/04/from-shadows-to-citizenship">Room for Debate: From Shadows to Citizenship</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/11/21/us/illegal-immigrants-divided-over-the-importance-of-citizenship.html">Illegal Immigrants Are Divided Over Importance of Citizenship</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/04/17/us/senators-set-to-unveil-immigration-bill.html">Beside a Path to Citizenship, a New Path on Immigration</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/04/05/us/politics/in-immigration-reform-path-to-citizenship-divides-and-confuses.html">Path to Citizenship Divides Congress and, Polls Show, Confuses Country</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2012/12/09/understanding-immigration-reform/path-to-citizenship-must-be-included">Room for Debate: Path to Citizenship Must Be Included</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/04/04/opinion/priced-out-of-citizenship.html">Priced Out of Citizenship</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/02/07/us/politics/group-of-young-immigrants-seeks-a-direct-path-to-citizenship-for-all-regardless-of-age.html">Group of Young Immigrants Seeks a Direct Path to Citizenship for All, Regardless of Age</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2009/02/15/us/15immig.html">U.S. Military Will Offer Path to Citizenship</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Reprieve From Deportation, Without Path to Citizenship:</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In June 2012, President Obama announced an executive action that gave a temporary reprieve to more than 800,000 undocumented young people. And last month, he announced another reprieve for an estimated five million more undocumented immigrants. Some people oppose these executive actions because they say the president bypassed Congress &#8212; and students can research that perspective below in the next teaching idea &#8212; but for the sake of this debate, what do you think about the policy change itself? Should undocumented immigrants with no criminal record be allowed to live and work in the United States without fear of being deported?</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/22/us/in-school-visit-obama-urges-congress-to-act-on-immigration.html">Amid Attacks, Obama Presses Congress to Move on Immigration</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/22/us/republicans-immigration-obama.html">Boehner Says Obamaâs Immigration Action Damages Presidency</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/21/us/obama-immigration-speech.html">Obama, Daring Congress, Acts to Overhaul Immigration</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/11/20/us/2014-11-20-immigration.html">What Is President Obamaâs Immigration Plan?</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/12/01/us/dream-act-gives-young-immigrants-a-political-voice.html">Young Immigrants Say Itâs Obamaâs Time to Act</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/08/14/us/young-immigrants-poised-for-deportation-deferral-program.html">Young Immigrants, in America Illegally, Line Up for Reprieve</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/06/16/us/us-to-stop-deporting-some-illegal-immigrants.html">Obama to Permit Young Migrants to Remain in U.S.</a></li>
</ul>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/09/learning/immigrationgraphLN/immigrationgraphLN-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/09/learning/immigrationgraphLN/immigrationgraphLN-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/12/09/learning/immigrationgraphLN/immigrationgraphLN-blog480.jpg" id="100000003280118" width="480" height="237" alt="Growth in the unauthorized immigrant population has slowed significantly since 2007, driven in part by a decline in immigrants from Mexico, where more than half of those immigrants were born. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/11/20/us/2014-11-20-immigration.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="237"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Growth in the unauthorized immigrant population has slowed significantly since 2007, driven in part by a decline in immigrants from Mexico, where more than half of those immigrants were born. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/11/20/us/2014-11-20-immigration.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Refugee Status</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/07/15/us/questions-about-the-border-kids.html">More than 68,000 children</a> have been apprehended at the border between the United States and Mexico this year, a sharp increase compared to last year, though the monthly totals have declined in recent months. A large number of these children have been <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/10/world/americas/fleeing-gangs-children-head-to-us-border.html">fleeing crime and violence</a> in their countries, and President Obama has called the situation a <a href="//www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-28203923">&#8220;humanitarian crisis.&#8221;</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Should many of these young unaccompanied minors from Central America be granted <a href="//www.uscis.gov/humanitarian/refugees-asylum">refugee status</a>, instead of just being deported? </p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//kaiserhealthnews.org/news/doctors-testimony-crucial-as-border-children-seek-asylum/">Kaiser Health News | Doctorsâ Testimony Crucial As Border Children Seek Asylum</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/01/us/obama-approves-plan-to-let-children-apply-for-refugee-status-in-central-america.html">Obama Approves Plan to Let Children in Central America Apply for Refugee Status</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.wsj.com/articles/illegal-immigrants-seeking-asylum-face-a-higher-bar-1411945370">The Wall Street Journal | Illegal Immigrants Seeking Asylum Face a Higher Bar</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/23/us/us-faces-suit-over-tactics-at-immigrant-detention-center.html">U.S. Faces Suit Over Tactics at Immigrant Detention Center</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2014/08/04/many-mexican-child-migrants-caught-multiple-times-at-border/">Pew Research Center | Many Mexican Child Migrants Caught Multiple Times at Border</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/20/us/rush-to-deport-young-migrants-could-trample-asylum-claims-.html">Rush to Deport Young Migrants Could Trample Asylum Claims</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/13/opinion/sunday/a-refugee-crisis-not-an-immigration-crisis.html">The Children of the Drug Wars: A Refugee Crisis, Not an Immigration Crisis</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/26/us/snakes-and-thorny-brush-and-children-at-the-border-alone.html">Snakes and Thorny Brush, and Children at the Border Alone</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/11/us/poverty-and-violence-push-new-wave-of-migrants-toward-us.html">Hoping for Asylum, Migrants Strain U.S. Border</a></li>
</ul>
