<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Teaching Idea #2: Researching and Responding to Obama&#8217;s Immigration Plan</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/21/us/obama-immigration-speech.html">speech</a> to the nation last month, President Obama said that Americaâs immigration system is broken and needs immediate fixing, even if Congress isn&#8217;t up to the job. As a temporary solution, he announced his plan to offer <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/11/20/us/2014-11-20-immigration.html">protection from deportation</a> for up to 5 million unauthorized immigrants. Do you agree with the president&#8217;s policy? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To begin, watch this <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/us/100000003247659/obamas-immigration-address.html">video</a> of the president&#8217;s 15-minute speech or have students trade off reading aloud from the full White House <a href="//www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/11/20/remarks-president-address-nation-immigration">transcript</a> of his remarks. As students listen, they should note or underline key facts the president cites to support his argument. (Before starting, teachers may wish to review the following vocabulary words: entrepreneurial, flout, bipartisan, undocumented, deportation, amnesty, impugning, hypocrisy.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The class can then spend a few minutes writing and sharing personal reactions to President Obamaâs speech in which they reflect on his description of the problem and his proposed solution. You may want to hold the discussion as a <a href="https://www.facinghistory.org/for-educators/educator-resources/teaching-strategies/four-corners">Four Corners</a> activity. On balance, do they believe he has made a persuasive case or are they skeptical? What questions do they still have?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To go deeper, students can work in groups or individually to research some or all of the questions below &#8212; along with any of their own questions they had after listening to the president. They then might design and present a poster that illustrates a question they researched, including key facts, quotations and their final conclusion. Or they can <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/07/for-the-sake-of-argument-writing-persuasively-to-craft-short-evidence-based-editorials/">write an evidence-based editorial</a> responding to the president&#8217;s plan.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Questions to Consider</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>1. What are the facts behind President Obama&#8217;s immigration plan?</strong><br />
This interactive feature, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/11/20/us/2014-11-20-immigration.html">&#8220;What Is President Obamaâs Immigration Plan?&#8221;</a>, provides a range of facts and statistics behind the presidentâs policy. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>2. How do immigrants feel about the presidentâs plan?</strong><br />
In these <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/22/us/immigration-deportation-planning-free-life.html">stories</a>, a range of immigrants share their feelings on President Obamaâs proposals; some are <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/21/us/politics/undocumented-immigrants-tune-in-to-see-president-fulfill-long-delayed-pledges.html">overjoyed</a> while others express <a href="//www.newyorker.com/business/currency/immigrants-excluded-obama-plan">frustration</a>. In this <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/us/100000003031733/one-family-faces-the-immigration-debate.html">video</a> recorded last summer, a family talked about the immigration changes they were hoping for.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>3. What do Republicans and Democrats say?</strong><br />
Some Republican governors have expressed <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/20/us/politics/-2014-11-20-us-republican-governors-seethe-over-obamas-immigration-move.html">fury</a> over the presidentâs plan, while other Republicans are taking a <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/21/us/politics/in-immigration-fight-some-in-gop-fear-alienating-latinos.html">more moderate</a> approach.  Some Democrats view the issue as <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/21/opinion/the-democrats-immigration-problem.html">politically perilous</a>, while others are <a href="//www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2014/11/with-immigration-obama-fulfills-his-promise-to-progressives/383022/">pleased</a> by what they see as the Obama administrationâs decisive action.  Polls <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/11/20/us/2014-11-20-immigration.html">show</a> that both parties are divided on the issue of immigration. This <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/us/politics/100000002329944/the-immigration-battle-explained.html">video</a> explains why Congress has had such a tough time passing a bill on the issue.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>4. What do ordinary Americans say? </strong><br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/11/20/us/2014-11-20-immigration.html">Polls show</a> that a majority of respondents believe that illegal immigrants should be allowed to stay in the United States if theyâre already here, while <a href="//www.people-press.org/2014/10/23/as-midterms-near-gop-leads-on-key-issues-democrats-have-a-more-positive-image/#other-issues-immigration-health-care-and-marijuana">less than half</a> believe that undocumented immigrants should be offered a pathway to full citizenship. More than 60 percent of respondents <a href="//www.pewresearch.org/key-data-points/unauthorized-immigrants-who-they-are-and-what-the-public-thinks/">strongly believe</a> that Congress should fix the problem with new legislation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>5. Is the President overriding Congress, and is that legal?</strong><br />
Legal experts are <a href="//www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2014/11/18/constitutional-limits-of-presidential-action-on-immigration-12">divided</a> over the question of whether President Obama is exceeding his constitutional authority by granting deportation exemptions to up to 5 million undocumented immigrants. Legal or not, Ross Douthat, a Times columnist, says that Mr. Obama has overreached and created the very thing he campaigned to prevent: an <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/23/opinion/sunday/ross-douthat-the-making-of-an-imperial-president.html">imperial presidency</a>.</p>
<hr/>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/10/31/world/JP-CATALONIA-LN/JP-CATALONIA-LN-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/10/31/world/JP-CATALONIA-LN/JP-CATALONIA-LN-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/10/31/world/JP-CATALONIA-LN/JP-CATALONIA-LN-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000003280210" width="480" height="320" alt="Watching a Sikh band performing at a temple in Badalona, a city in Catalonia, Spain.Â Up to 1.5 million residents in the region are not citizens and therefore cannot vote. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2012/10/31/world/europe/catalonias-immigrants-add-to-separatist-debate.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Watching a Sikh band performing at a temple in Badalona, a city in Catalonia, Spain.Â Up to 1.5 million residents in the region are not citizens and therefore cannot vote. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/10/31/world/europe/catalonias-immigrants-add-to-separatist-debate.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Edu Bayer for the International Herald Tribune</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Teaching Idea #3: Comparing Immigration Policies and Attitudes Around the World</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">How unique are Americaâs immigration challenges? Pick one or more nations from the list below, or from <a href="//query.nytimes.com/search/sitesearch/?action=SearchSubmit&#038;pgtype=Topic#/immigration">your own choosing</a>, and research the situation they face with regard to immigration or migrants. Prepare a class presentation in which you compare and contrast the situations in different countries and highlight any potential solutions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Australia:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/27/world/asia/australia-alarms-rights-groups-with-deal-to-resettle-refugees-in-cambodia.html">Australia Alarms Rights Groups With Deal to Resettle Refugees in Cambodia</a></li>
<li><a href="//latitude.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/04/new-australian-immigration-policy-hurts-afghan-refugees/">Coming to Australia</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Brazil:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/15/world/americas/immigrants-stir-new-life-into-sao-paulos-gritty-old-center.html">Immigrants Stir New Life Into SÃ£o Pauloâs Gritty Old Center</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>France:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/25/world/europe/in-french-port-city-calais-a-real-psychosis.html">In French Port City, âa Real Psychosisâ</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/31/world/europe/european-border-agency-reports-surge-in-illegal-migration.html">European Agency Reports Surge in Illegal Migration, Fueling a Debate</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Germany:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/08/world/in-german-city-rich-with-history-and-tragedy-tide-rises-against-immigration.html">In German City Rich With History and Tragedy, Tide Rises Against Immigration</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/09/world/europe/christian-social-union-plan-immigrants-speak-german-at-home.html">Party Backs Off German-Only as a Suggestion for Immigrants</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/19/world/europe/needing-skilled-workers-a-booming-germany-woos-immigrants.html">Needing Skilled Workers, a Booming Germany Woos Immigrants</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Jordan:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/05/09/world/middleeast/zaatari.html">Syrian Refugees Struggle at Zaatari Camp</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Lebanon:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/09/05/world/middleeast/Syrian-Refugees-in-Lebanon.html">The Refugees</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Malta:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/21/world/europe/shipwreck-survivors-recount-a-deadly-journey-from-middle-east-to-europe.html">Shipwreck Was Simple Murder, Migrants Recall</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/09/23/world/europe/malta-struggles-under-wave-of-african-migrants.html">A Tiny Mediterranean Nation, Awash in Immigrants With Nowhere to Go</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Mexico:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/22/world/americas/mexico-makes-route-tougher-for-migrants.html">Mexico Makes Route Tougher for Migrants</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/09/24/world/americas/mexicos-expatriates-mix-praise-and-criticism.html">Mexicoâs New Arrivals Mix Praise and Criticism</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/09/22/world/americas/for-migrants-new-land-of-opportunity-is-mexico.html">For Migrants, New Land of Opportunity Is Mexico</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/09/22/world/americas/migration-to-mexico.html">Migration to Mexico</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Myanmar:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/03/15/world/asia/trapped-between-home-and-refuge-burmese-muslims-are-brutalized.html">For Myanmar Muslim Minority, No Escape From Brutality</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Netherlands</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2011/08/14/world/europe/14dutch.html">Amid Rise of Multiculturalism, Dutch Confront Their Questions of Identity</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Norway:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/24/world/europe/anti-immigrant-party-norway.html">Amid Debate on Migrants, Norway Party Comes to Fore</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Saudi Arabia:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/29/saudi-arabia-foreign-labour-crackdown-migrants">Saudi Arabia&#8217;s Foreign Labour Crackdown Drives Out 2m Migrants</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Spain:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/10/31/world/europe/catalonias-immigrants-add-to-separatist-debate.html">Immigrants Have Helped Set Catalonia Apart in Spain</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Sweden:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/21/opinion/sunday/syrian-refugees-nordic-dilemma.html">Scandinavians Split Over Syrian Influx</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/13/world/europe/rift-emerges-in-sweden-over-immigration.html">Rift Emerges Before Vote in Sweden as Immigration Tests a Tradition of Openness</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/world/europe/100000000659641/sweden-immigration.html">Sweden&#8217;s Immigrant Identity</a> (video)</li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Switzerland:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/01/world/europe/swiss-voters-reject-move-to-restrict-foreign-workers.html">Swiss Voters Reject Move to Restrict Immigrants</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Thailand:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/19/world/asia/thailand-is-searching-for-scores-of-uighurs-who-fled-china.html">Thailand Is Searching for Scores of Uighurs Who Fled China</a></li>
</ul>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>United Kingdom:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/01/business/international/david-cameron-pulls-back-from-the-brink.html">Cameron Pulls Back From the Brink</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/nov/27/david-cameron-european-union-immigration">Cameron to Tell EU: Cut All Tax Credits to Migrants</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/11/29/world/europe/in-northern-ireland-immigrants-are-increasingly-met-with-fists.html">In Northern Ireland, a Wave of Immigrants Is Met With Fists</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/oct/26/british-towns-swamped-immigrants-michael-fallon-eu">British Towns Being âSwampedâ by Immigrants, Says Michael Fallon</a></li>
</ul>
